Topological Sorting
-------------------

Topological sorting for Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) is a linear ordering of vertices such that for every directed edge uâ†’v, vertex u comes before v in the ordering. 
There may be several topological orderings for a graph.

Note: Topological Sorting for a graph is not possible if the graph is not a DAG.



==========================================

static void findTopo(int node,int vis[],ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>> adj,Stack<Integer> st)
{
		vis[node]=1;
		for(Integer it:adj.get(node))
		{
		if(vis[node]==0)
			findTopo(node,vis,adj,st)
		}
		
		//push the elements after visiting all its neighbours
		st.push(node);


}

static ArrayList<Integer> topoSort(ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>> adj)
{
	int n=adj.size();
	Stack<Integer> st=new Stack<>();
	int vis[]=new int[n];
	
	for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
	{
	if(vis[i]==0]
	{
	findTopo(i,vis,adj,st);
	}
	}
	
	ArrayList<Integer> topoList=new ArrayList<>();
	//Popping elements from stack and pusing into list
	while(!st.isEmpty())
	{
		topoList.add(st.pop());
	}
	return topoList;
}



=============================

Time Complexity: O(V+E). We visited all the nodes, and all the neighbours of each node(i.e., all the edges).
Auxiliary Space: O(V). For visited array, and for stack to store the topological order.
